{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613983"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:40:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:40:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16335"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16335"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116453"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9026"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16335"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98452"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7515"},{"type":"tags","id":"7521"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21476"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116453"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe crystalline lens is an important refractive structure in the eye that helps focus light onto the retina.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical arrangement of the crystalline lens?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Located posterior to the vitreous humour","Anchored by zonular fibres to the ciliary body","Directly attached to the cornea","Connected to the retina by ligaments","Suspended within the anterior chamber"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe crystalline lens is \u003Cstrong\u003Eanchored by zonular fibres to the ciliary body\u003C/strong\u003E. These zonular fibres (also called suspensory ligaments) allow the lens to change shape during accommodation when the ciliary muscles contract or relax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lens is not \u003Cstrong\u003Elocated posterior to the vitreous humour\u003C/strong\u003E as it is actually anterior to the vitreous humour and posterior to the iris. The lens is not \u003Cstrong\u003Edirectly attached to the cornea\u003C/strong\u003E since these structures are separated by the anterior chamber and iris. The lens is not \u003Cstrong\u003Econnected to the retina by ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E as there are no direct connections between lens and retina. The lens is not \u003Cstrong\u003Esuspended within the anterior chamber\u003C/strong\u003E because it is located posterior to the iris between the posterior chamber and vitreous chamber.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lens is a transparent, biconvex structure that, along with the cornea, helps to focus light onto the retina. Its position and attachment to the ciliary body via zonular fibres is crucial for the process of accommodation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The crystalline lens is a transparent biconvex structure located between the iris and vitreous humour.","The lens is suspended by zonular fibres that attach it to the ciliary body, allowing for accommodation.","The lens focuses light onto the retina by changing shape through the process of accommodation."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98452"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16335"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98452"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:11:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:15:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9026"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116453"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4941"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updated